This cephalopod inspired robot is a ghoulish spektor that haunts archeotech ruins.

It is a remix of Akewea's Sci-Fi Sphere Drone (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5266420) and Franklima260's Mini Servo Arm (https://cults3d.com/en/3d-model/game/sci-fi-sphere-drone)

The arms are fully posable with ball & socket joints at the shoulder, elbow, and wrist.

Since the attachment point to the base is pretty small, I've included 4 additional versions of the tentacles with a rod cutout for pinning of the following sizes
- 1mm brass rod (1.1mm hole)
- 1.5mm brass rod (1.6mm hole)
- 0.8mm thin paperclip (0.9mm hole)
- 1.15mm thick paperclip (1.25mm hole)

Alloteu (https://cults3d.com/en/users/Alloteu/3d-models) is the original designer of Lawdogs. Evilamericorp (https://cults3d.com/en/users/evilamericorp/3d-models) & Dimkaf (https://cults3d.com/en/users/dimkaf/3d-models) took his models, reposed them, and added additional bits to create alternate models.

I just took Evilamericorp's and Dimkaf's creations, removed the non-Lawdog stuff and collected them together so you could quickly access additional Lawdog models.

Note these guys have no heads! But I've included 3 of Alloteu's Lawdog Heads (with a ball, cylinder, or hole at the bottom) for you to use.

item.title: [GRATUIT] Cults3d > Nedius > 28mm_32mm_Female_and_Male_Heads_Resource [non dl]
item.description:

Id objet : 28mm-32mm-female-and-male-heads-resource

Collections pour tags :

  • 28mm SFDIV HUMAINS Sf-tous-types-humains Bits Builders NONDL NONSUP

Description :

1
2
3
4
5

For a variety of projects I've got on, I needed a set of human heads to add to models I intend to sculpt for 3D printing. I couldn't find any I like, so have made up a collection of heads I've created by scratch sculpting, using Blender Add-ons, etc. None are 'stock' generation. Each has been scratch sculpted, re-sculpted from add-on generated blank faces, modified, re-shaped etc by me to meet the needs of my projects for 28mm - 32mm scale miniatures. 

I really struggled to find any free base heads I could use as a starting block to model onto, so am putting these here as a resource for any other amateur enthusiast designers like me who need a start until our scratch-sculpting talents get to where they need to be!

If you do use them in your own projects, would love to see them.

Besides Warmaster, Mordheim was the other Specialist Games wargame I always wanted to sink into. I had the chance to play a few games with my club back then, but the interest faded away in the group. I though it would be interesting to check whether it works in 10mm so I quickly assembled a Reiklander mercenary warband for testing purposes. I guess these will not be that useful for others, the minis are quite specific, but at lest they can be useful if I ever want to do an empire Warmaster army.

Here is the roster:
Captain - sword, pistol (85)

Champion - halberd (45)
Youngblood - spear, bow (35)

4 Marksman - crossbow (4x50)

Here are several Ronin stands from my entire 10mm samurai army. The entire army can be purchased at a choose your own price here: https://darkgref.gumroad.com/l/ddWNC. The entire army includes 15 different historical and fantasy units.

The rest of the army pieces on Thingverse can be found here:

I use an Ender 3 Pro with a .4mm nozzle, update CURA and set to high detail.

These cannot be used for commercial purposes unless you buy the commercial license on my Gumroad site.


From the wikipedia page on Ronin
n feudal Japan (11851868), a rnin (/ronn/ ROH-nin; Japanese: , IPA: [oi], 'drifter' or 'wanderer', lit.'a person of the waves')[1] was a samurai who had no lord or master and in some cases, had also severed all links with his family or clan. A samurai becomes a rnin upon the death of his master, or after the loss of his master's favor or legal privilege.[2][3]

In modern Japanese, the term is usually used to describe a salaryman who is unemployed or a secondary school graduate who has not yet been admitted to university.[4][5]
Etymology

The word rnin is usually translated to 'drifter' or 'wanderer'; however, per kanji, r () means "wave" (as in body of water) or "unrestrained", while nin () means "man" or "person". It is an idiomatic expression for 'vagrant' or 'wandering man', someone who finds the way without belonging to one place. The term originated in the Nara and Heian periods, when it referred to a serf who had fled or deserted his master's land. In medieval times, the Ronin were depicted as the shadows of samurai, master-less and less honorable. It then came to be used for a samurai who had no master (hence the term 'wave man' illustrating one who is socially adrift).[3]
Status

According to the Bushido Shoshinshu (the "Code of the Warrior"), a samurai was supposed to commit seppuku (also harakiri, "belly cutting", a form of ritual suicide) upon the loss of his master.[6][7] One who chose not to honor the code was "on his own" and was meant to suffer great shame. The undesirability of rnin status was mainly a discrimination imposed by other samurai and by daimy, the feudal lords.[citation needed]

Like other samurai, rnin wore two swords.[8] Rnin used a variety of other weapons as well. Some rninusually those who lacked moneywould carry a b (staff around 1.5 to 1.8 m (5 to 6 ft)) or j (smaller staff or walking stick around 0.9 to 1.5 m (3 to 5 ft)) or a yumi (bow). Most weapons would reflect the ry (martial arts school) from which they came if they were students.[citation needed]

During the Edo period, with the shogunate's rigid class system and laws, the number of rnin greatly increased. Confiscation of fiefs during the rule of the third Tokugawa shgun Iemitsu resulted in an especially large increase of rnin.[2] During previous ages, samurai were able to move between masters and even between occupations. They could also marry between classes. However, during the Edo period, samurai were restricted, and wereabove allforbidden to become employed by another master without their previous master's permission.[citation needed]

Because the former samurai could not legally take up a new trade, or because of pride were loath to do so, many rnin looked for other ways to make a living with their swords. Those rnin who desired steady, legal employment became mercenaries that guarded trade caravans, or bodyguards for wealthy merchants. Many other rnin became criminals, operating as bandits and highwaymen, or joining organized crime in towns and cities. Rnin were known to operate or serve as hired muscle for gangs that ran gambling rings, brothels, protection rackets, and similar activities. Many were petty thieves and muggers. The criminal segment gave the rnin of the Edo period a persistent reputation of disgrace, with an image of thugs, bullies, cutthroats, and wandering vagrants.[2] After the abolition of the Samurai, some of the ronin continued with their thuggery and their mercenary work and activities, such as participating in the infamous assassination of Korean Empress Myeongseong of the Joseon Dynasty in 1895, the Eulmi Incident.[citation needed]
History
Graves of the forty-seven rnin at Sengaku-ji

Until the Sengoku period, peasants accounted for the majority of daimy armies, so they accounted for the majority of ronin.[citation needed]

Especially in the Sengoku period, daimy needed additional fighting men, and even if a master had perished, his rnin was able to serve new lords. In contrast to the later Edo period, the bond between the lord and the vassal was loose, and some vassals who were dissatisfied with their treatment left their masters and sought new lords. Many warriors served a succession of masters, and some even became daimy. As an example, Td Takatora served ten lords. Additionally, the division of the population into classes had not yet taken place, so it was possible to change one's occupation from warrior to merchant or farmer, or the reverse. Sait Dsan was one merchant who rose through the warrior ranks to become a daimy.[citation needed]

As Toyotomi Hideyoshi unified progressively more significant parts of the country, daimy found it unnecessary to recruit new soldiers. The Battle of Sekigahara in 1600 resulted in the confiscation or reduction of the fiefs of large numbers of daimy on the losing side; consequently, many samurai became rnin. As many as a hundred thousand rnin joined forces with Toyotomi Hideyori and fought at the Siege of Osaka. In the ensuing years of peace, there was less need to maintain expensive standing armies, and many surviving rnin turned to farms or became townspeople. A few, such as Yamada Nagamasa, sought adventure overseas as mercenaries. Still, the majority lived in poverty as rnin. Their number approached half a million under the third Tokugawa shgun Iemitsu.[citation needed]

Initially, the shogunate viewed them as dangerous and banished them from the cities or restricted the quarters where they could live. They also prohibited serving new masters. As rnin found fewer options, they joined in the Keian Uprising of 1651. This forced the shogunate to rethink its policy. It relaxed restrictions on daimy inheritance, resulting in fewer confiscations of fiefs, and it permitted rnin to join new masters.[citation needed]

Not having the status or power of employed samurai, rnin were often disreputable and festive,[2] the group targeted humiliation or satire. It was undesirable to be a rnin, as it meant being without a stipend or land. As an indication of the shame felt by samurai who became rnin, Lord Redesdale recorded that a rnin killed himself at the graves of the forty-seven rnin. He left a note saying that he had tried to enter the service of the daimy of Chsh Domain but was refused. He killed himself, wanting to serve no other master and hating being a rnin. On the other hand, the famous 18th-century writer Kyokutei Bakin renounced his allegiance to Matsudaira Nobunari, in whose service Bakin's samurai father had spent his life. Bakin voluntarily became a rnin, and eventually spent his time writing books (many of them about samurai) and engaging in festivities.[citation needed]

In the 19th century, Emperor Meiji abolished the Samurai class and any status the ronin had died with them.[citation needed]

Gotrek was another story. "Every battlefield the Hostile Environment Troops find themselves on, is a hostile, bombarded and chemically saturated one. Taking trenches, cities and sectors require troops in the thousands, and waiting for weeks or months on end for the right moment to strike. To that end, Command uses Shock Assault Troops, Specialists in lightning warfare.

Other armies decorate these soldiers in honors, having them as elite regiments on their planets. The best of the best.
Not so for the Hostile Environment Troops, for in the hellish condition they find themselves in, a simple hole in their suits means they are living on borrowed time.
Most, but not all, Shock Assault are penal legionaires, promised freedom if they survive a single attack on an enemy position. Very few survive to see reinforcements, fewer still survive long enough for a commissar to excuse them of their sins and turn them free men and women.

The life of a Shock Assault Trooper is a short and deadly life, but their sacrifices turn the tide of battle, saving thousands.

Enlist Today!"

Using the fantastic model made by FELIXTHECRAZY (along another Ridgerunner proxy that dissapeared time ago and i dont know who made it), i designed this vehicle mostly for my Squat miners, but i think is suitable for Genestealers Cults too.

I cant assure if is a proper Ridgerunner proxy, because i think this model is smaller, but i added all the weapons and accesories listed in GSC army book for the vehicle in case that someone want to use it in that way. Maybe re-escaling it a bit is enough, but i dont how much, i have never seen a real Ridgerunner model before.

The original model is a single piece, meant to be printed in resin, but my experience printing vehicles in resin is not the best, so i prefer print them on PLA. With that in mind, i separated some pieces of the model to make it suitable for FDM printers, specially small parts that will probably break when you try to remove supports, then the best is print them apart and glue them after. Refer the pics to look where each piece goes

Weapons and accesories are small and detailed, and were designed to be printed in resin. You can try to print them in FDM of course, but they will lost a lot of detail, specially with the mining laser.

About the Spotter, i choose a more "technological" option instead a guy with binoculars. It makes more sense i think, and it saved me a lot of work :P

I included the center hull as one piece and in halves. I printed it as one piece, but I think it's easier and faster to print two pieces. Your choice.

I dont discard make some aditional weapons and accesories in the future.

Remixed some of my paleolithic people to make some units for Grudge. What is Grudge? Its a crunchy little (but still one-sheet) mini-agnostic narrative campaign that Ill Gotten Games is designing for their CRUX: Universal Wargaming rules. It plays in parts as a bloody familial feud and farming sim. Find out more on the IGG Patreon or through DutchMogul here on Thingiverse.

I call these four the Wulfstrael Family, composed of Mother Wulfstrael (who carries a knife and does the butchering.) Old Man Wulfstrael, who dispatches livestock with his trusty hammer, and their two daughters, Hilda and Editha, who hunt game with their bows. The family generally deals in meat and hides, raising cattle, sheep and pigs, but also tanning and preparing pelts and hides for trade.

Here are twelve, perhaps crude, though definitely brutal close combat hand-to-hand melee assault weapons. They are intended to allow give you some extra options and conversion bits for your Chaos Cultists. You do love Chaos Cultists don't you?? Though I think they are generic enough to work for most human sized miniatures in any grim and dark dystopian future setting from undercity gangs, to wasteland scavengers, rebels, organized criminal thugs, and pretty much any kind of poorly equipped ne'er-do-wells up to no good.

-- Axe
-- Club
-- Hammer1
-- Hammer2
-- Knife1
-- Knife2
-- Mace
-- Pick
-- Pipe
-- Scimitar
-- Sword1
-- Sword2

Each weapon comes in three STL variants:
1) weapon by itself
2) weapon held in a right hand
3) weapon held in a right hand (hand has a nub to socket into wrists)

Knife1 and Knife2 have four variants each, two with the blade held normally and two with the blade held ready to stab. You can mirror the weapons with hands on them to create left-handed versions. All total that comes to 68 different options. You can use these files for physical or digital conversions as you see fit. They are also Creative Common Licensed so that you can modify them as you please and then share your own innovations.

Enjoy, and may the Dark Gods favor you.

The Underhive Poverty Outreach Team are made up of the members of the Noble Houses. They are equipped with special suits of armor, which they use to stock the many food banks found in the Underhive.

Horace's role in the team, as the bionic tray-holder guy, is to descend the many flights of stairs from Tesco (Spire branch) to the underhive with an entire pallet of donated tinned pineapple chunks in each hand. His powerfists come with a secondary weapon of two rows of firework-launchers which he keeps loaded in hope of a Labour Party victory - when it finally comes after 38,000 years.

IT'S THE LATE 80's, IN SPAAAAACE!

Everyone has mohawks and piercings!
Industrial Metal head anarchists galore!

Here are a few heavy weapons options for your human sized dudes and dudettes, Inspired by classic Necromunda. I give you low tech solutions to deadly problems.

The BRRT Supression Stubber:
All style and zero substance with this over designed chunk of metal, it'll throw roughly bullet shaped things in a roughly straight line. You'll need steroids top deal with kick up though.

Australian Stubber:
The bullets go in ..... UPSIDE DOWN!?
That's right, make gravity your accomplice when you mow down a MF with this retro gravity fed SOB.

Firehazard:
Loaded with homemade fuel that you can dink in a pinch to get your liver upset, the fire hazard is dangerous to everyone, that's cool right? OSHA are nerds!

BAGL (The Ga-chunk):
The Bow Assisted Grenade Launcher or the BAGL (sometimes called the Ga-chunk!) on account of the sound it makes.
Who says you need fancy gas assisted launching mechanisms? Who had the bright idea to try and launch explosives with smaller explosions?
That guy is dead, because those Ideas are hard to execute.

Why go complicated when you can just update a medieval stonebow with modern polymers and alloys.

Possibly the only "stealth" grenade launcher on the market!

Resin would be Ideal, but I've printed the smaller assault rifles I made on FDM and they barely look any more trash than other necromunda weapons! (0.2 nozzle is necessary)

I would suggest just printing the "drones sampler" file as it makes 1 of each size and type of drone, all the bases, and 3 sets of weapons.

These could work as cultists or angry peasants as well.

***UPDATE: 2020-08-18***
I uploaded revised models. After printing and receiving feedback from others, I modified the designs to make the models thicker. The models should now be sturdier, making it easier to trim away supports and play with the models without ankles and halberd hafts snapping.
*******************************

I remixed a pile of files from Thingiverse, mostly from EvilFrog (whose stuff is great!), in order to make a full regiment of Empire halberdier strips for the game Warmaster. These are 10mm scale, and would work for late medieval / renaissance troops as well, though nobody fought with a halberd and a shield historically, as a halberd takes two hands to wield. I also included a 40x20x2mm unit base. I highly recommend printing these strips in resin, with supports, at 0.025mm layer height. That's what I plan to do.

We at Ill Gotten Games are big fans of the [Vintage RPG Podcast](https://www.stitcher.com/podcast/unwinnable-3/the-vintage-rpg-podcast), and after designing a model for Hambone [the hammer-wielding ranger, Johan](https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3483772)), I made one for Stu as well. This is Greel, an opportunistic (but deep down, gold-hearted) ex-mercenary company leader/current warlock with a magic ring that can turn him into a tree at the first sight of danger. The model prints without support.

If you haven't checked it out, Hambone and Stu (Horvath, from [unwinnable.com](https://unwinnable.com/)) do a weekly podcast where they discuss tabletop games, and do deep dives into RPGs old and new. This all branches off of Stu's excellent [Instagram feed](https://www.instagram.com/vintagerpg/?hl=en), which is always an insightful read if you're into the history and current state of tabletop roleplaying games. We're proud to be [supporting them on Patreon](https://www.patreon.com/vintagerpg/overview), and you should really check out what they're doing/throw them some bones if you like it as much as we do.

Toxic Rat  London. Another of Banksys rats shows a rat with a barrel of toxic waste spilling across the pavement. Several copies have been seen around LA, but none have been confirmed as being by Banksy. This original one is now barely visible.

This model is part of a series I remixed just to see if it was possible. Here are the rest of them.
